3:23 p.m. - Record by the Court who based upon his inclination denies the request to amend counterclaim. Atty. Robinson to submit the orders.
3:24 p.m. - Response by Atty. Oettinger as to his position.
3:27 p.m. - Court goes off the record to schedule hearing as to attorney fees.

Attorney Andrew Oettinger in court for Plaintiff Thirty Star Hospitality, LLC. Attorney Charles W. Pollard in court for Defendant Lakewood WWV Camp, Inc.. Plaintiff Thirty Star Hospitality, LLC in court. Attorney Jamie A. Robinson in court by Zoom for Defendant Lakewood WWV Camp, Inc.. Attorney Christopher E. Kentra in court by Zoom for Defendant Lakewood WWV Camp, Inc. Court in session @ 1:01 p.m. Appearances made. Matter before the Court for hearing as to undertaking. Court addresses rent and turns to Atty. Oettinger as to what rent would be for the golf course. Response/record by Atty. Oettinger. Court swears Jeff Broaden who responds to Court's questions regarding rent. Objection by Atty. Kentra as to evidentiary hearing and motion filed right before Court. Court has not seen the motion, and is not intending on taking evidence, but more an offer of proof. Further record by the Court as to attorney fees currently incurred. Court addresses PL as to other damages for better explanation.

1:11 p.m. - Response/argument by Atty. Kentra who objects to the amounts suggested and potential damages. Response by the Court to the argument of Atty. Kentra. Further argument/discussion with Atty. Kentra as to rent vs. expenses.
1:20 p.m. - Response/argument by Atty. Oettinger in response to Atty. Kentra's arguments. Further record as to deadline for filing appeal - which has not been done by deadline of 1:00 p.m. today.
1:24 p.m. - Court addresses Atty. Kentra as to surety they intend to use as undertaking. Response by Atty. Kentra that they intend to post cash.

1:27 p.m. - Record by the Court that the amount of damages could easily reach the amount of $1,000,000.00 and sets the undertaking at this amount. Response by Atty. Kentra who asks for time to figure out how he is going to post that amount. Response by the Court a to 10 day period of time for the Sheriff's Department to execute WRIT and if he is able to get bond by that time, Court will get him into Court to see if he will approve, but will not delay this proceedings any longer. Atty. Oettinger to prepare order from this hearing.09-23-2021Motion

Attorney Nina G Beck in court for Plaintiff Thirty Star Hospitality, LLC. Attorney Andrew Oettinger in court for Plaintiff Thirty Star Hospitality, LLC. Attorney Charles W. Pollard in court for Defendant Lakewood WWV Camp, Inc.. Attorney Christopher E. Kentra in court. Court in session @ 9:34 a.m. Appearances made. Matter before the court on motions after verdict. Record by the Court as to his review of briefs, research, and his inclinations regarding motions. Court is inclined to deny the motions after verdict and to let the verdict stand. Court is also inclined to deny the motion for new trial.
9:38 a.m. - Parties have no further argument.

9:38 a.m. - Record by the Court who stands by his inclination and denies the defense motions. Atty. Oettinger to submit order denying defense motions. Court addresses judgment of eviction. Atty. Kentra is not objecting to the order. Court addresses Writ of Restitution. Response/record by Atty. Kentra who will be filing a notice of appeal which would make discussion regarding undertaking premature at this time.  Response by Atty. Oettinger as to requirements of the defendant if they wish to stay writ of restitution. Atty. Oettinger asks that the Writ of Restitution be signed today. Response by Atty. Kentra who will be filing the notice of appeal and undertaking today. Discussion as to stay of WRIT and damages hearing.
9:46 a.m. - Court goes off the record to allow attorneys to discuss amount of undertaking and to see if they can reach an agreement.

10:17 a.m. - Court back in session. Record by Atty. Oettinger as to discussion with counsel and informs the Court that they gave the defendant number of $1,000,000.00 for undertaking. Atty. Kentra is not able to agree to that number until he speaks to his client. Based upon record, Atty. Oettinger asks that the WRIT be signed so they can move forward. If the defendant agrees to the amount of the proposed undertaking.
10:19 a.m. - Response by Atty. Kentra who asks the Court for briefing schedule if needed as to the amount of undertaking requesting.  Further discussion.
10:22 a.m. - Court sets matter for Thursday, September 23, 2021 @ 1:00 p.m. Atty. Oettinger will agree to stay the WRIT until Thursday at 1:00 p.m.
Clerk will set up Zoom for those attorneys who wish to appear that way.
Court in recess @ 10:24 a.m.

Hearing scheduled for September 23, 2021 at 01:00 pm.09-13-2021Response/reply

07-28-2021Jury trialReddy, David M.Adams, Adrianne
Additional text:
Attorney Nina G Beck in court for Plaintiff Thirty Star Hospitality, LLC. Attorney Daniel J Blinka in court for Plaintiff Thirty Star Hospitality, LLC. Attorney Jamie A. Robinson in court for Defendant Lakewood WWV Camp, Inc.. Attorney Jamie A. Robinson in court for Defendant Lakewood WWV Camp, Inc.. Attorney Charles W. Pollard in court for Defendant Lakewood WWV Camp, Inc.. Attorney Christopher E. Kentra in court. Court in session @ 8:23 a.m. Appearances made. Matter before the Court for one (1) day jury trial. Court addressees attorneys and thanks them for joint statement of the case and jury questions/instructions.

8:24 a.m. - Atty. Blinka makes a record as to issues with a couple of DE Exhibits and how they reference their clients. Further record/argument as to reference to "charity" when describing their clients. Response by Atty. Kentra. Court will allow defendants to refer to defendant as Lakewood Veteran's Charity. Further record/argument by Atty.. Kentra as to demonstrative exhibits that the defendant intends to use. Response/argument by Atty. Blinka. Response by the Court who will allow the photos of the golf course, but will not allow photos of group outings/veterans. Record by Atty. Kentra as to demonstrative exhibit. Response/objection by Atty. Blinka as to relevance. Response by the Court who agrees with Atty. Blinka and will not allow that demonstrative.

8:36 a.m. - Record by Atty. Beck as to special verdict forms and whether Court want to address them at this time or after close of evidence. Response by Atty. Robinson as to new proposed verdicts. Court reviews. Court will address special verdict form after evidence is in.  Plaintiff has nothing further at this time.

8:39 a.m. - Atty. Robinson as to jury instruction they want to add definition of "rent" from Blacks Dictionary and submits it for review by the Court.  Objection/record by Atty. Blinka. Response by the Court who will consider this at the jury instruction conference later today.
8:42 a.m. - Court goes over voir dire procedures and instruction #50 that he will read to the final panel.
OFF THE RECORD, JURY CLERK SWEARS POTENTIAL JURORS AND SEATS 12 IN THE BOX FOR VOIR DIRE.
BAILIFFS:  JAN CHAMBERS, NANCY LYON, AND KIM MADAUS (TRAINING)

8:51 a.m. Court in session with same appearances. Court addresses the jury and explains process of voir dire, and reads the statement of case to the jury. Attorneys introduce themselves and their witnesses. Court addresses jurors as to any COVID concerns. No hands.
9:01 a.m. - Voir Dire by the Court.
9:06 a.m. - Voir Dire by Atty. Blinka
9:11 a.m. - Voir Dire by Atty. Pollard
9:18 a.m. - Court goes off the record to allow parties to take their strikes.
9:33 a.m. - Back on the record - Clerk excuses struck jurors. Court goes off the record while other jurors are excused from the courtroom.
9:35 a.m. - Clerk swears the panel. Judge reads the preliminary instructions to the jury.

9:39 a.m. - Court excuses jurors for morning break. Court addresses attorneys as to panel - both sides are satisfied with the panel as chosen. Record by the court as to sidebar with attorneys as to selection. Attorneys agree. Court goes off the record for morning break.
10:09 a.m. - Court back in session with same appearances. No objection to preliminary instructions by anyone. Witness appearing by zoom is brought through.
10:10 a.m.  - Jury seated in jury box. Court addresses panel and reads preliminary instructions.
10:13 a.m. - Opening Statement by Atty. Blinka
10:30 a.m. - Opening Statement by Atty. Kentra

10:38 a.m. - PL calls Anthony Klok who is duly sworn by the Court and responds to direct examination of Atty. Beck. Exhibits #1, #4, #5, #8, #10 (previously marked and received by stipulation) identified and testified to by the witness.
11:12 a.m. - Cross examination by Atty. Robinson.
11:27 a.m. - Redirect by Atty. Beck
11:35 a.m. - Recross by Atty. Robinson

11:40 a.m. - PL calls Jeff Broaden who is duly sworn by the Court and responds to direct exam of Atty. Blinka. Exhibits #6, #7 (previously marked and received by stipulation), identified and testified to by the witness. Exhibit #29, previously marked, identified and testified to by the witness. Atty. Blinka moves Exhibit #29 into evidence. No objection. Exhibit received.
11:58 a.m. - Jury excused for lunch. Parties have nothing for the record. Court in recess for lunch.

1:01 p.m. - Court back in session with same appearances. Court addresses Atty. Kentra's request to reconsider ruling as to exhibits deemed inadmissible. Response by the Court who reads case law into the record. Atty. Kentra responds to further questions by the Court. Response by Atty. Blinka who asks what specific testimony was presented the "opened the door". Response/further argument by Atty. Kentra. Atty. Robinson responds to further questions of the Court. Response by the Court who addresses Plaintiff as to their position. Response/record by Atty. Blinka. Response by the Court who does not believe that direct examination did not "open the door", and will not allow the demonstrative exhibit.

1:10 p.m. - Jury seated in jury box, and Mr. Broaden retakes the stand, and responds to cross examination by Atty. Robinson. Exhibit #25, previously marked, identified, and testified to by the witness. DE moves exhibit #25 into evidence. No objection. Exhibit received.
1:24 p.m. - Court in recess for short side bar with attorneys regarding exhibit #31.
1:27 p.m. - Court back in session. Redirect by Atty. Blinka.
1:28 p.m. - Recross by Atty. Robinson.
1:29 p.m. - Witness excused. Plaintiff Rests

1:29 p.m. -  DE calls Daniel McClean who is duly sworn by the Court and responds to direct examination of Atty. Kentra. Exhibits #116. previously marked, identified and testified to by the witness. Atty. Kentra moves exhibit into evidence. No objection. Exhibit received. Exhibit #113, previously marked, identified and testified to by the witness. Atty. Kentra moves exhibit #113 into evidence. Objection by Atty. Blinka that property in question is related to the is matter as it is not on the golf course property. Court denies admission of #113. Exhibit #114, previously marked, identified and testified to by the witness. Atty. Kentra moves exhibit into evidence -  no objection. Exhibit received. Exhibit #117 moved into evidence - denied. Exhibit #120 identified by the witness. Atty. Kentra moves exhibit into evidence. No objection. Exhibits received.
2:10 p.m. - Court off the record for sidebar as to line of questioning.
2:14 p.m. - Court back in session with same appearances. Direct examination by Atty. Kentra continues.
2:17 p.m. - Court in recess for afternoon break.

2:34 p.m. - Court back in session with attorneys. Record by the Court as to side bar regarding exhibit #31 - parties have nothing to add to Court's record. Record by the Court as to side bar regarding questions concerning other business disputes - parties have nothing to add. Discussion as to jury instructions.
2:39 p.m. - Jury seated in jury box. Cross examination of Mr. McClean by Atty. Blinka.
3:04 p.m. - Redirect by Atty. Kentra

3:05 p.m. - Witness excused. DE calls Maia Wilson who is duly sworn by the Court and responds to direct examination of Atty. Kentra. Exhibit #123, previously marked, identified and testified to by the witness. Atty. Kentra moves exhibit into evidence. Objection by Atty. Beck as to relevance. Court sustains objection but will allow further questions. Court denies admission of exhibit. Exhibit #122, previously marked, identified and testified to by the witness. Atty. Kentra moves exhibit into evidence. Objection by Atty. Beck as to relevance. Response by Atty. Kentra. Court denies admission of exhibit. Direct examination continues. Exhibit #111 previously marked, identified and testified to by the witness. Atty. Kentra moves exhibit into evidence. No objection - exhibit received. Exhibit #112, previously marked, identified and testified to by the witness. Atty. Kentra moves exhibit into evidence. No objection. Exhibit received.
3:27 p.m. - Cross Examination by Atty. Beck.
3:41 p.m. - Witness excused. Defendants rest. No rebuttal. Evidence is closed. Jury excused from the courtroom.
3:42 p.m. - Court addresses jury instructions and special verdicts off the record.

4:48 p.m. - Court back in session with the attorneys. Record by the Court as to jury instruction conference and special verdict discussion. Further record as to special instruction regarding rent definition. Response/record by Atty. Robinson as to her objection to denial of the instruction.
4:55 p.m. - Jury seated in jury box. Court reads instructions to the panel.
5:05 p.m. - Closing argument by Atty. Blinka
5:17 p.m. - Closing argument by Atty. Robinson
5:34 p.m. - Court reads special verdict form to the panel as well as final instructions regarding filling out the form. Final jury instructions also given to panel by the Court.
5:37 p.m. - Jury retires to jury room for deliberations.
No objections to the reading of instructions by either party. Record by the Court as to side bar regarding rebuttal argument. Parties have nothing further. Court in recess.

6:20 p.m. - Court back in session with same appearances. Jury has reached a verdict. Jury seated in jury box. Court addresses foreperson, Michael Felland as to verdict. Court reads verdict to the parties.  Clerk polls the jurors at the request of Atty. Robinson.
6:22 p.m. - Jury is excused. Court in recess to speak to the jurors.

6:24 p.m. - Court back in session with same appearance. Court addresses attorneys as to motions after verdict and if they apply to small claims eviction matter. Further discussion. Motions to be filed by deadline. Matter set for motions after verdict if any are filed.

Court in recess @ 6:39 p.m. Motion hearing scheduled for September 20, 2021 at 09:30 am.07-28-2021Proposed jury instructions
Additional text:
Joint Proposed Jury Instructions
07-28-2021Other papers
Additional text:
Joint Statement of the Case and Stipulation as to Undisputed Facts
07-27-2021Pre-trial conferenceReddy, David M.Adams, Adrianne
Additional text:
*Transcript filed 11/2/21* Attorney Daniel J Blinka in court for Plaintiff Thirty Star Hospitality, LLC. Attorney Nina G Beck in court for Plaintiff Thirty Star Hospitality, LLC. Attorney Jamie A. Robinson in court for Defendant Lakewood WWV Camp, Inc.. Attorney Charles W. Pollard in court for Defendant Lakewood WWV Camp, Inc.. Court in session @ 3:32 p.m. Appearances made. Matter before the Court for final pre-trial.

3:32 p.m. - Court addresses motion for reconsideration first. Record by the Court as to motion and based upon Court's analysis and denies the motion for reconsideration. Court addresses parties as to issues in this case and goes over 5 issues separately.

3:34 p.m. - Attorney Robinson responds to Court's questions regarding each issue. Atty. Robinson has no issue as to #1. As to #2 - acceptance of rent. Response/argument by Atty. Robinson. Response by the Court.
3:38 p.m. - Response/argument by Atty. Robinson as to reconcile the two statutes.
3:38 p.m. - Response/argument by Atty. Beck.

3:40 p.m. - Court addresses proper notice. Response/record by Atty. Robinson as to issue of notice - and 14 day notice was provided rather than 28 day notice. Discussion. No other issues for trial per Atty. Robinson.
3:45 p.m. - Response/argument by Atty. Blinka regarding to the issues stated by the Defendants and that sub 4 of the statute controls here.
3:49 p.m. - Response/argument by Atty. Robinson.

3:50 p.m. - Argument/responses as to periodic tendency, termination of lease. Continued argument as to payment of rent.  Atty. Robinson responds to questions of the Court as to attempted payment of rent.
4:01 p.m. - Atty. Blinka responds to further questions of the Court as to attempted payment of rent.

4:02 p.m. - Response by the Court that he believes that this issue as to tenancy is something that should be determined as a matter of law. Response by Atty. Robinson who believes this is an issue that should be presented to the jury.
4:05 p.m. - Discussion as to special jury instruction prepared by Atty. Beck. Atty. Robinson also provides proposed jury instructions. Court goes off the record to review proposed instructions.

4:08 p.m. - Back on the record. Court addresses proposed instructions with the parties. Court is inclined to name the issue as to creation of periodic tendency is the issue for the jury to decide. Depending on what they find, Court will determine notice as matter of law. Response by Atty. Robinson as to oral modification argument of the Plaintiff. Response by the Court who reads from the instruction as to this issue. Atty. Beck responds to further questions of the court as to this issue.
